'''Patrick S.A. Flood''' (born September 12, 1951) is an American politician from [[Maine]]. Flood is a [[Maine Republican Party|Republican]] [[Maine State Senate|State Senator]] from [[Maine]]'s 21st District, representing part of [[Kennebec County, Maine|Kennebec County]], including [[Hallowell, Maine|Hallowell]] and [[Gardiner, Maine|Gardiner]].. He was first elected to the [[Maine State Senate]] in 2012 after serving from 2004-2012 in the [[Maine House of Representatives]].<ref name="PVS">{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/36830/patrick-flood#.UN9F22-1VLs|title=Senator Patrick Flood Biography -  Project Vote Smart|work=[[Project Vote Smart]]|accessdate=29 December 2012}}</ref>

As a member of the House of Representatives, Flood served from 2010-2012 as the House chairman of the budget-reviewing Appropriations Committee. In June 2012, incumbent Republican State Senator [[Earle McCormick]] withdrew from the general election after facing an uncontested renomination for District 21. Flood was named his replacement.<ref name="MPBN2012">{{cite news|url=http://www.mpbn.net/Home/tabid/36/ctl/ViewItem/mid/3478/ItemId/22349/Default.aspx|title=Maine Rep. Flood to Seek Maine Senate Seat|date=June 20, 2012|work=[[Maine Public Broadcasting Network]]|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=29 December 2012}}</ref> He defeated Democrat former State Representative [[David Bustin]] in the November general election by approximately 300 votes.<ref name="KJ2012">{{cite news|url=http://www.kjonline.com/news/Flood-defeats-Bustin-in-Senate-21-race.html|title=Flood defeats Bustin in Senate 21 race | The Kennebec Journal, Augusta, ME|coauthors=Staff report|date=November 7, 2012|work=[[Kennebec Journal]]|accessdate=29 December 2012}}</ref>

He has worked with [[International Paper]] since 1974.<ref name="PVS"/>

In 1974, Flood earned a B.S. from the [[State University of New York College of Environmental Science and Forestry]] in Natural Resource Management.<ref name="PVS"/>

